<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="subsec-intr-separable" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Introduction to Separable ODEs</title>

  <p>
    We now introduce a method for solving a broad class of first-order ODEs called <term>separable differential equations</term>. Let's first get a feel for the idea through an example before formalizing things.
  </p>

 <p>
  Let's get a feel for the idea through an example before formalizing things. Consider the differential equation <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = e^y x^2</m>. Notice that the right-hand side factors into a part involving only <m>y</m> and a part involving only <m>x</m>. This suggests we try to "separate" the variables, moving all the <m>y</m> terms to one side and all the <m>x</m> terms to the other.
</p>
<p>
  We write:
  <me>\frac{1}{e^y}\, dy = x^2\, dx.</me>
  We are treating <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> as if it were a fraction and "multiplying both sides by <m>dx</m>." Strictly speaking, <m>\frac{dy}{dx}</m> is not a fraction. We will justify why this manipulation is mathematically valid shortly. For now, think of it as a useful shorthand that consistently gives the right answer.
</p>
<p>
  Integrating both sides:
  <me>\int \frac{1}{e^y}\, dy = \int x^2\, dx.</me>
  Each side produces its own constant of integration:
  <me>-e^{-y} + C_1 = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + C_2 \implies -e^{-y} = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + \underbrace{C_2 - C_1}_{=\, C},</me>
  so we write:
  <me>-e^{-y} = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + C.</me>

</p>
<p>
      So the general solution is <m>y = -\ln\!\left(-\frac{1}{3}x^3 - C\right)</m>.
</p>
<solution>
  <title>Algebra to solve for <m>y</m></title>
  <p>
    Starting from <m>-e^{-y} = \frac{1}{3}x^3 + C</m>:
    <md>
      <mrow>e^{-y} \amp= -\frac{1}{3}x^3 - C \amp\amp \text{(multiply both sides by } -1\text{)}</mrow>
      <mrow>-y \amp= \ln\!\left(-\frac{1}{3}x^3 - C\right) \amp\amp \text{(take ln of both sides)}</mrow>
      <mrow>y \amp= -\ln\!\left(-\frac{1}{3}x^3 - C\right) \amp\amp \text{(multiply both sides by } -1\text{)}</mrow>
    </md>
    So the general solution is <m>y = -\ln\!\left(-\frac{1}{3}x^3 - C\right)</m>.
  </p>
</solution>
 <p>
  This will outlined more clearly on the next page. But for now, let's make sure you 
  understand what a first order separable ODE is. 
 </p>
<exercise xml:id="ex-mc-separable">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Recall that a separable ODE is one that can be written in the form <m>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(y)g(x)</m>, where the right-hand side factors into a part involving only the dependent variable and a part involving only the independent variable. Which of the following ODEs are separable? Select all that apply.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <choices randomize="yes">
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dP}{dt} = 3P</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Separable! We can write this as <m>f(P) = P</m> and <m>g(t) = 3</m> (or <m>f(P) = 3P</m> and <m>g(t) = 1</m>). The right-hand side factors cleanly into a part in <m>P</m> and a constant.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dv}{dt} = v - vt^2</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Separable! Factor out <m>v</m> from the right-hand side: <m>v - vt^2 = v(1 - t^2)</m>. So <m>f(v) = v</m> and <m>g(t) = 1 - t^2</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2\sin(x)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Separable! The right-hand side already factors as <m>f(y) = y^2</m> and <m>g(x) = \sin(x)</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 + 1</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Separable — but sneaky! There is no explicit <m>x</m> on the right-hand side, so <m>g(x) = 1</m> (a constant function). We have <m>f(y) = y^2 + 1</m> and <m>g(x) = 1</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dy}{dx} = y^2 + x</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not separable! There is no way to write <m>y^2 + x</m> as a product <m>f(y) \cdot g(x)</m> — the two variables are added together, not multiplied.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dv}{dt} = v + t</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not separable! Like the previous option, <m>v + t</m> cannot be factored into a part in <m>v</m> only and a part in <m>t</m> only. Addition is the giveaway here.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>\frac{dy}{dx} = \sin(x + y)</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Not separable! Even though it involves a trig function, <m>\sin(x+y)</m> cannot be written as <m>f(y)g(x)</m> — the variables are tangled together inside the sine.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>
  </choices>
</exercise>


